TYPE="Letter Legal Financial Claim"><PB N="[1]"><OPENER><DATELINE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE><NAME
TYPE="place">Washington City</NAME></ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><DATE
VALUE="1857-11-11">Nov 11, 1857.</DATE></DATELINE><SALUTE><ABBR
EXPAN="Honorable">Hon</ABBR><LB>Sec. of the Treasury,<LB>Sir,</SALUTE></OPENER><P>As the attorney of the <NAME
TYPE="place">North Carolina</NAME> <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> permit me to present for your consideration an act of Congress passed in their favor which bears date <DATE
VALUE="1848-07-29">July 29, 1848</DATE>, and two decisions made thereon by two of your predecessors, <UNCLEAR><ABBR
EXPAN="Messieurs">Messr.</ABBR></UNCLEAR> <NAME REG="Mr." TYPE="person">Corwin</NAME> &amp; <NAME
REG="Mr." TYPE="person">Guthrie</NAME> the former establishing a construction which was reversed by the latter, to the great injury of the Indians.  The act referred to will be found in the 9th vol <NAME
TYPE="place">U S.</NAME> laws, page 264.</P><P><Q REND="block">Sec. 4.  Be it enacted <ABBR
EXPAN="et cetera">&amp;c</ABBR> That the Secretary of War cause to be ascertained the number and names of such individuals and families including each member of every family of the <NAME
TYPE="place person">Cherokee nation</NAME> of Indians that remained in the State of <NAME
TYPE="place">North Carolina</NAME> at the time of the ratification of the treaty of <NAME
TYPE="place">New Echota</NAME>, <DATE VALUE="1836-05-23">May twenty three eighteen hundred and thirty six</DATE>, and who have not removed west of the <NAME
TYPE="place">Mississippi</NAME>, or received commutation for removal and <ORIG
REG="subsistence">subsistance</ORIG>, and report the same to the Secretary of the Treasury: Thereupon the <EMPH>Secretary of the Treasury shall set apart, out of any moneys in the treasury not otherwise appropriated</EMPH><PB
N="[2]"> a sum equal to fifty three dollars and fifty three cents for each individual ascertained as aforesaid and that he cause to be <EMPH>paid to every such individual or his or her legal representative interest at the rate of six, percent per annum on such per capita from the said <DATE
VALUE="1836-05-23">twenty third day of May eighteen hundred and thirty six</DATE> to the time of the passage of this act and continue <ORIG
REG="annually">annully</ORIG> thereafter the said payment of interest at the rate aforesaid.</EMPH></Q></P><P>Under the recited act the census was taken and the sum of &dollar;53.33 set apart in the Treasury for each <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokee</NAME> embraced on the Census Roll prepared by <NAME
TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Major">Maj</ABBR> John C. Mullay</NAME>, which in the aggregate amounted <ADD
PLACE="supralinear">to</ADD> &dollar;80.901.61</P><P>In the year of <DATE
VALUE="1850-00-00">1850</DATE>, as the attorney of the <NAME TYPE="place">North Carolina</NAME> <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> I made application to the second auditor for the payment of interest due to the legal representatives of deceased <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME>, for whom the investment  <SIC CORR="had">had had</SIC> been made.  The auditor refused to make payment and<PB
N="[3]"> referred the question of payment to the Secretary of the Treasury, the <ABBR
EXPAN="Honorable">Hon</ABBR> <NAME TYPE="person">Wm M. Meredith</NAME>.  The letter of the second Auditor making the reference bears date <DATE
VALUE="1850-01-09">9th Jan. 1850</DATE> and is hereunto appended marked, A.</P><P><DEL
TYPE="overstrike">The letter of the <ABBR EXPAN="2nd">2d</ABBR> Auditor</DEL> It was referred to the <ABBR
EXPAN="2nd">2d</ABBR> Comptroller for his decision thereon, by the Secretary of the Treasury.</P><P>On the <DATE
VALUE="0000-01-12">12th of <ORIG REG="January">Janurary</ORIG></DATE> his decision of the question was made as shown by his letter of that date hereunto appended marked B, in which he decided that the interest had to be paid to the legal representatives of the Indians while the Government as trustee retained the possession of the fund.  He says, to use his own language, <Q
REND="block"><EMPH>in case of the death of a person interested in the fund the legal representative of such person would succeed to his rights and might claim the interest so long as the fund continued.  This is in accordance with the language of the 4th section.</EMPH></Q></P><PB
N="[4]"><P>This decision was adopted by the Secretary of the Treasury <NAME
REG="Wm. M." TYPE="person">Mr Meredith</NAME> and concurred in to <UNCLEAR>effect</UNCLEAR> by his successor the <ABBR
EXPAN="Honorable">Hon</ABBR> <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Thomas">Ths.</ABBR> H Corwin</NAME>, and by his assistant <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Hodge</NAME>, as shown by his letter to <NAME TYPE="person">Col A M Mitchell</NAME> the disbursing agent under date of <DATE
VALUE="1851-07-14">July 14, 1851</DATE>, hereunto appended marked C.  In which specific instructions are given with reference to making payment to the legal representatives of deceased <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME>,<Q REND="block"><EMPH>you will be governed by the following general principles<LB>To all Indians of lawful age now living payment of the respective sums due to each to be made to the Indians direct.<LB>All sums due to minor children now deceased to be paid to the parents of living.<LB>In cases of deceased wife or husband the amount due to be paid to the Survivor.<LB>In all such instances where the deceased left neither husband nor wife (as the case</EMPH>may be) then to be paid to the<PB
N="[5]"><EMPH>legal representative</EMPH></Q></P><P>Under these instructions the payments were made and the amount of the agent settled and thus approved by the accounting offices of the Treasury Department.</P><P>On the <DATE
VALUE="1853-03-03">3rd of March 1853</DATE>, <NAME TYPE="person">Mr Corwin</NAME> went out and <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Guthrie</NAME> came in to office, from that date I am inclined to believe that in the year <DATE
VALUE="1853-00-00">1853</DATE> an examination of your office will prove that the principle adopted of paying the interest of deceased <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> to their legal representatives received the sanction of <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Guthrie</NAME> himself.</P><P>Be that as it may, on the <DATE
VALUE="1854-01-15">15th of Jan 1854</DATE> <NAME TYPE="person">Mr Guthrie</NAME> by himself or most probably by a subordinate in his office, attempted the change of the construction of the <ADD
PLACE="supralinear">law</ADD> and the established practice under it and to reverse the decision of his predecessors <UNCLEAR><ABBR
EXPAN="Messieurs">Messr</ABBR></UNCLEAR> <NAME REG="Mr. Wm. M." TYPE="person">Meredith</NAME> &amp; <NAME
REG="Mr." TYPE="person">Corwin</NAME> and the accounting officers of the Treasury department,</P><PB
N="6"><P>Evidence of which is found in the instructions to the agent <NAME
TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="James">Jas</ABBR> W Terrell</NAME>, appointed to pay the interest under date of <DATE
VALUE="1854-01-15">Jan 15th 1854</DATE>, hereunto appended marked <EMPH>D</EMPH> which for reasons herein after set forth it is presumed should be set aside and the first construction of the law adopted in the payment of the interest now remaining deed.</P><P>In the instructions referred to which appear to have been signed; but never examined by <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Guthrie</NAME>, the following is the then opinion upon the payment of the interest<Q
REND="block"><EMPH>It has been decided that the annuity in every case ceases with the death of the Indian, and that the proper representative of such Indian can receive only the annuity up to the time of his death.  In all such cases therefore you will make the compensation at the rate of &dollar;6.39, per annum</EMPH> from the <DATE
VALUE="1851-07-29">29th of July 1851</DATE> to<PB N="7"> the day of the death of the Indian and pay the representatives of the amount due according to such computation instead of the amount assumed to be due in the statement.</Q></P><P>The foregoing opinion contains conclusive evidence that <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Guthrie</NAME> never examined either it or the law to which it refers, I will repeat the evidence on which this assertion is based.  The law made provision for the payment of six percent interest upon the sum of &dollar;53.33, which gives as the annual payment &dollar;3.19 98/100.  In the opinion of <NAME
TYPE="person">Mr Gutherie</NAME> or one of his subordinates it is said after stating that the interest would not be paid after the death of the Indian, it is stated that the agent would make the rate of <EMPH>compensation at the rate of &dollar;6.39 per annum, from the <DATE
VALUE="1851-07-29">29th of July 1851</DATE> to the day of the death of the Indian</EMPH>, can any one imagine that the <ABBR>HonHonorable</ABBR> Secretary of the Treasury of the <NAME
TYPE="place">United States</NAME> would have committed this error if he had<PB
N="8"> examined either the law or the opinion.  If he had examined the law he would have seen that it was but six percent allowed the Indian, giving annual annuity of &dollar;319. 98/100, if he had examined the decision he would have seen that it was allowing twelve instead of six percent interest double as much as authorized by the law.  The conclusion therefore seems <ORIG
REG="irresistible">irresistable</ORIG> that the opinion over this signature was not his opinion because it will not do to adopt the opposite conclusion <DEL
TYPE="overstrike">because then it would be supposed</DEL> that he was incapable of calculating simple interest.</P><P>But in addition to the absurd <UNCLEAR>contradiction</UNCLEAR> in the opinion reputed to Mr. <UNCLEAR><NAME
REG="Mr." TYPE="person">Gutherie</NAME>'s</UNCLEAR> it is in direct opposition to the views entertained by Congress upon making payment to the <NAME
TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> of the principal as shown by the act of <DATE
VALUE="1855-00-00">1855</DATE> chap 204<PB N="[9]"> page 700, <Q TYPE="block">And be it further <UNCLEAR>enacted</UNCLEAR> That the Secretary of the interior is hereby authorized and required to cause to be paid to the <NAME
TYPE="place">North Carolina</NAME> <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> embraced in the roll of <NAME
TYPE="person">John C Mullay</NAME> <EMPH>or the legal representative of each of them as have died since their <ORIG
REG="enrollment">enrolment</ORIG></EMPH> the sum of fifty three dollars and thirty three cents respectively for the expenses of their removal and subsistence now held in trust by the <NAME
TYPE="place">United States</NAME>, according to the terms of the 4th section of the act of <DATE
VALUE="1848-07-29">twenty ninth July Annodomini eighteen hundred and forty eight</DATE>.</Q></P><P>I have now shown that the accounting offices of the Treasury and his secretaries decided in favor of paying interest to the legal representative of the Indians while the Government retained the possession of the principal.</P><PB
N="[10]"><P>I will now try to prove that neither <NAME TYPE="person">Mr. Guthrie</NAME> nor the President of the <NAME
TYPE="place">United States</NAME> had any power to change the <ORIG
REG="decision">dicision</ORIG> of the accounting <UNCLEAR>officers</UNCLEAR> of the Treasury.  To establish this position I beg to leave to refer you to the opinion of <NAME
TYPE="person">William Wirt</NAME> Attorney General vol 1. p 624, given upon the construction of the laws establishing the Treasury Department, In which opinion he says,<Q
REND="block">With regard to the comptroller it directs that is shall be his duty to superintend the adjustment and preservation of all public accounts settled by the Auditor and certify the balance arising thereon to the Register no right of appeal <EMPH>from his decision to the President</EMPH>, (see act of <DATE
VALUE="1809-03-03">3rd March 1809</DATE>, vol 4 p 221, sec 2) makes it the duty of the comptroller to direct the Auditor<PB
N="[11]"> to audit and settle any particular amount and to report such settlement for his revision and final decision, so also the act of <DATE
VALUE="1817-03-03">3rd March 1817</DATE>, which introduces the present organization of the Treasury Department <LB>Thus in every instance <EMPH>the decision of the Comptroller is declared to be final</EMPH> and it is manifest that the law contemplates no further examination by any officer, after such decision.</Q></P><P>But in addition to law plain Justice is on the side of the Indian.  The Government has his money and had also millions held in trust for the different tribes.  If she can claim that the interest does not descend to the heirs and legal representatives of the <NAME
TYPE="place">North Carolina</NAME> <NAME TYPE="place">Cherokees</NAME> may she not extend the decision to all the tribes, and thus defeat the objects of the Government in creating annuities.</P><CLOSER><SALUTE>Your <ABBR
EXPAN="obedient servant">obt servt</ABBR></SALUTE></CLOSER><SIGNED><NAME
TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="William">Wm</ABBR> H Thomas</NAME></SIGNED></DIV1></BODY></TEXT></TEI.2>
